            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "reinvented", speaker = "The Child With the List",
                text = "*(The child's eyes go wide, and they sit up straight, the parchment forgotten.)* There's — there's *another* one? *(barely breathing.)* A girl doing *exactly* this? *(and then, slowly, something even bigger dawns, too big for the small face to hold all at once.)* ...And a *choir*, and — you said *nobody taught us.* *(they look at their list, then up at you.)* So I didn't — I thought I *invented* it. The list. I thought I was the *only* one *clever* enough, or *sad* enough, to *think* of it. *(quietly, wonder replacing pride.)* But if there's a *Lula*, and a *choir*, and an *indexer*, all doing the *same thing*, in *different places*, *never* having *met* — *(their voice fills with something like awe)* — then it's not *my* idea. It's not *anybody's* idea. It's just — a *thing that's true*, that *keeps getting found*, by whoever *looks* at the *subtraction* and *can't stand* it. *(they grip the list.)* That means — that means even if *I* stop, even if they *make* me stop, even if I *grow up* and get *busy* and *forget* — *somewhere*, some *other* serious child is *starting their own list*, *right now*, because *Maman Bell* happened to *them* too, with a *different name.* *(they look up, and the serious face breaks into a fierce, hopeful smile.)* You *can't kill it.* The *remembering.* You'd have to make *every* child in *every* age *not mind* the *subtraction* — and *some* of us *always* will. *(they bend back to the list, writing harder.)* I'm not the *only* one. I'm just the *one that's here.* That's — that's *better*, actually. That's *so much* better. Thank you for telling me I'm not *alone* in it.",
