            {
                id = "subtraction", speaker = "The Child With the List",
                text = "*(The child considers the question with the deep seriousness of someone who has thought about little else.)* Where I learned to see it. *(they pick at the parchment's edge.)* ...I don't think anybody *learns* it. I think everybody *knows* it, when they're *small*, and then most people *un-learn* it, because it's *too sad* to *keep* knowing. *(quietly.)* When you're little, you think *everything* that *exists* will *always* exist. Your house. Your Maman. The *cat.* And then *one* of them *goes* — for me it was Maman Bell, next door — and you find out the *terrible* secret nobody *warns* you about: that things can *stop being*, and the *world doesn't even wobble.* *(they look up, grave.)* That's the *subtraction.* Not just that she *died* — everybody *knows* people die. It's that she died and *the world filled in the space so fast* it was like she'd *never made a dent.* Like a *stone* dropped in a *pond* that doesn't even *ripple.* *(fiercely.)* And once you've *seen* that — *really* seen it — you can either *un-see* it, like the grown-ups do, so you can be *cheerful* — or you can *decide* it's *not allowed*, and spend your life *making ripples* where the world tried to *close up smooth.* *(they tap the list.)* The list is *ripples.* Every name is me saying *\"the pond is* not *allowed to* forget *this stone fell.\"* *(they shrug, small and certain.)* I just never *un-saw* it, is all. That's the only difference between me and the cheerful grown-ups. I *remember* being *small* and finding out things can *stop.* And I *minded.* I never *stopped* minding.",
                autoNextNodeId = "close",
