            g.nodes.Add(new DialogueNode
            {
                id = "names", speaker = "The Child With the List",
                text = "*(The child takes up their writing-stub with immediate, businesslike focus, and the care they bring to it is its own small heartbreak.)* Halen. *(they print it slowly.)* H-A-L-E-N. A potter. *(they look up.)* I'll write *potter* next to it, so it's not just a *name*, it's a *person who did something.* *(they write.)* Maerys. A soldier. *(carefully.)* M-A-E-R-Y-S. And — Sariel? *(they get the spelling right.)* A weaver. *(they finish, and study the three new names with satisfaction.)* There. *(quietly.)* Ten thousand years, you said. They were forgotten ten thousand years. *(they touch the names.)* But they're not *now.* They're on *my list.* In *good* handwriting. With what they *did* written next to them. *(they look up at you, fierce and certain.)* That's the thing the grown-ups don't understand about the list. They think it's about the *dead.* It's not. *Halen* doesn't *know* he's on it. It can't *help* him. *(they tap their own chest.)* It's about *me.* About *deciding* I'm the *kind* of person who *writes the name down* instead of the kind who *lets the pond close.* *(they carefully roll the list.)* When you write somebody's name, you don't *save them.* You can't. They're *gone.* You just — you *change what kind of world it is*, by a *tiny* bit. From a world where they were *forgotten*, to a world where *one* serious child *wrote them down careful.* *(they look up.)* That's worth doing. Even if it's *small.* *Especially* because it's small. Small is the only size that's *always* available.",
